                <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11/1698: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-04-05T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 5, 1933—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received April 5—1:54 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>307. My 305, April 4, 3 p.m.<note n="48" xml:id="d727fn48">Not printed.</note>
                    The following telegram has been received from Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“April 4, 9 p.m. Soong asks me to telegraph you that the communist
                            situation is extremely serious, three divisions of Government troops
                            having been defeated south of Nanchang within last few days. The
                            supposedly crack Eleventh Division lost one-third, the Fifty-second and
                            one other practically destroyed. Chiang left for Nanchang this morning.
                            Soong states this new disaster greatly aggravates the Government’s grave
                            financial position and the need for postponement of the indemnity
                            payments. He hopes that you will treat this as far more than an ordinary
                            situation. He expressed anxiety for your reply.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
